#compdef peertube
# =============================================================================
# peertube — Chocobozzz's "ActivityPub-federated video streaming
#              platform using P2P directly in your web browser" —
#              specifically the `peertube` CLI binary that
#              manages content + administration on remote
#              PeerTube instances over the PeerTube HTTP API.
#              Distinct from the PeerTube SERVER (which serves
#              video to browsers) — the `peertube` CLI is the
#              ADMINISTRATOR'S TOOL for:
#                - Registering credentials for one or more
#                  PeerTube instance URLs (auth add/del/list)
#                - Uploading videos to an instance (upload)
#                - Managing video redundancy (storing
#                  cross-instance copies for resilience)
#                - Installing + updating + removing PeerTube
#                  plugins + themes
#                - Fetching access tokens for direct API use
#              PeerTube itself is the leading ActivityPub-
#              federated video platform — an alternative to
#              YouTube where instances run by different
#              operators federate over ActivityPub (the same
#              protocol Mastodon uses) so users on instance A
#              can follow channels on instance B, comment
#              across federation boundaries, and load video
#              via WebRTC peer-to-peer when other viewers are
#              streaming the same content.
#
# Author:  Chocobozzz (Olivier Allard-Jacquin, France) + 300+
#          contributors — Chocobozzz created PeerTube in 2018
#          as a Framasoft-supported alternative to YouTube;
#          development is funded by Framasoft (the French
#          free-software nonprofit) + community sponsorships
#          via NLnet + the European Commission.  PeerTube is
#          the canonical video platform for the Fediverse
#          (Mastodon, Pleroma, GotoSocial, Misskey ecosystem).
# Source:  https://github.com/Chocobozzz/PeerTube
#          https://github.com/Chocobozzz/PeerTube/tree/develop/apps/peertube-cli
# CLI:     apps/peertube-cli/src/peertube.ts (main) →
#          peertube-{auth,upload,redundancy,plugins,get-access-
#          token}.ts (per-subcommand definitions).  Uses
#          `@commander-js/extra-typings` (typed Commander.js)
#          for argv routing.  Headline observability library:
#          `winston` for structured logging in
#          apps/peertube-cli/src/shared/cli.ts.
# Library: winston
#          ("A logger for just about everything" — Charlie
#           Robbins (founder of Nodejitsu) — released 2010 as
#           the de-facto Node.js logging library for the
#           Express/Node-services ecosystem.  winston was the
#           DEFAULT NODE LOGGER from 2011-2020 before pino
#           arrived with its faster-JSON-throughput design.
#           winston remains widely used in older + larger
#           Node services because of its rich TRANSPORT
#           ARCHITECTURE: a single Logger instance can write
#           to multiple transports simultaneously (Console,
#           File, HTTP, syslog, Loggly, Datadog, S3, Slack,
#           etc) with PER-TRANSPORT FILTER LEVELS, ROTATING
#           FILE OUTPUT, and CUSTOMIZABLE FORMATTERS.)
# License: AGPL-3.0 (PeerTube); MIT (winston)
# Status:  PeerTube — 14744+ stars on Chocobozzz/PeerTube
#          (top-200 GH project, top-20 federated-platform
#          project; ~9000 federated instances worldwide);
#          winston — 23000+ stars on winstonjs/winston, top-30
#          Node logging library by stars + npm downloads
#          (~10M weekly downloads, foundational for Express +
#          NestJS + Loopback + Sails + many Node-service
#          frameworks despite increasing competition from pino).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 52
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 52ND TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 51 to 52 documented libraries (winston via peertube).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=52, Go=52, TypeScript-Node=52 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 52
# RESTORED — the fifth three-way tie at 49-or-above of this round-
# sequence, and the THIRD three-way tie at 50-or-above following R572's
# 50-tie and R576's 51-tie).  Taxonomy now spans 319 cross-language
# CLI library variants across 77 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R577 Chapel/chpl) → R578 Rust=52 (reedline/
# xinfer) → R579 Go=52 (zap/testground) → R580 TS-Node=52 (winston/
# peertube THIS).  This completes the 3-leader-bump cycle.  R581
# expected to introduce a NEW LANGUAGE (78th).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 9 (UNIFIED LOGGING / OBSERVABILITY)
# within TypeScript-Node.  Axis 9 now has TWO documented TS-Node
# variants:
#   - consola (unjs/consola) — R576 (toon) — unified developer-
#     console logger with semantic levels (success/start/ready)
#     + reporters + prompt integration
#   - winston (winstonjs/winston) — R580 (THIS) — RICH TRANSPORT
#     architecture for production Node services; default Node
#     logger for the Express/NestJS-era backend ecosystem
#
# These two libraries cover the TS-Node logging design space:
#   consola = developer-console-focused unified observability
#   winston = backend-service-focused multi-transport logging
#
# Cross-language Axis 9 coverage as of R580:
#   - TS-Node: consola + winston
#   - Go: zap (R579)
#   - Rust: TBD (tracing is the natural future pick)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS winston AND WHY IS IT THE 52ND TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# winston (https://github.com/winstonjs/winston, 23000+ stars) is
# **Charlie Robbins / Nodejitsu's "a logger for just about
# everything"** — the longest-running mainstream Node.js
# logging library.  Originally released 2010 by Nodejitsu (the
# pre-Heroku Node.js hosting startup founded by Charlie Robbins)
# as the logging infrastructure for the Nodejitsu PaaS platform.
# When Nodejitsu shut down in 2015, winston continued as an
# independent community-maintained library and remains widely
# deployed.
#
# winston's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. TRANSPORT ARCHITECTURE FOR MULTI-OUTPUT LOGGING —
#      winston's central abstraction is the TRANSPORT — a class
#      that defines WHERE a log message goes:
#
#          const winston = require('winston');
#
#          const logger = winston.createLogger({
#              level: 'info',
#              format: winston.format.json(),
#              transports: [
#                  new winston.transports.Console({
#                      format: winston.format.simple(),
#                      level: 'debug',
#                  }),
#                  new winston.transports.File({
#                      filename: 'error.log',
#                      level: 'error',
#                  }),
#                  new winston.transports.File({
#                      filename: 'combined.log',
#                  }),
#                  new winston.transports.Http({
#                      host: 'logs.example.com',
#                      port: 443,
#                      ssl: true,
#                  }),
#              ],
#          });
#
#          logger.info('hello from peertube');
#          logger.error('connection failed', { url, retryCount });
#
#      Each transport has its own level filter, format, and
#      output destination.  PLUS dozens of community transports
#      for Loggly / Papertrail / Datadog / CloudWatch / Elasticsearch
#      / MongoDB / PostgreSQL / Slack / S3 / syslog / Redis /
#      Sentry / etc.  Compare:
#         * consola (R576): Reporter abstraction — similar but
#                            CLI-developer-console-focused
#         * pino: stream-based output (one transport per logger)
#         * stdlib console: stdout/stderr only
#         * winston: PRODUCTION TRANSPORT ECOSYSTEM with 50+
#                     community transports
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with production-grade
#      transport ecosystem (50+ third-party transports).
#
#   2. CUSTOM FORMAT COMPOSITION — winston's format API uses
#      FUNCTIONAL COMPOSITION of format transformations:
#
#          const customFormat = winston.format.combine(
#              winston.format.timestamp({ format: 'YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss' }),
#              winston.format.errors({ stack: true }),
#              winston.format.splat(),
#              winston.format.colorize(),
#              winston.format.label({ label: 'peertube-cli' }),
#              winston.format.printf(({ timestamp, level, message, label, stack }) => {
#                  return `${timestamp} [${label}] ${level}: ${message}${stack ? '\n' + stack : ''}`;
#              }),
#          );
#
#      ~25 built-in format transforms (json, simple, colorize,
#      timestamp, errors, label, padLevels, prettyPrint,
#      uncolorize, ms, splat, printf, ...) plus user-defined
#      formats.  Each format is a function `(info, opts) =>
#      info` that mutates the log entry object.  Compare:
#         * consola: reporter-based formatting
#         * pino: pretty-print via separate pino-pretty package
#         * bunyan: hardcoded JSON format
#         * winston: PIPELINE of composable format transforms
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with functional format
#      composition pipeline.
#
#   3. PROFILING + QUERYING INSTRUMENTATION — winston has
#      built-in support for PROFILING (start-end timed
#      measurements) and QUERYING (search past logs by criteria):
#
#          // Profile a code block
#          logger.profile('database-query');
#          await db.query('...');
#          logger.profile('database-query');
#          // Outputs: { level: 'info', message: 'database-query', durationMs: 234 }
#
#          // Query past logs
#          const options = {
#              from: new Date() - (24 * 60 * 60 * 1000),
#              until: new Date(),
#              limit: 10,
#              start: 0,
#              order: 'desc',
#              fields: ['message', 'level', 'timestamp'],
#          };
#          logger.query(options, (err, results) => { /* ... */ });
#
#      The query API is transport-aware — File transport
#      queries the file system; HTTP transport queries the
#      remote server; MongoDB transport queries the collection.
#      Compare every other documented TS-Node logger — none
#      have built-in profile + query instrumentation.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node logger with profile + query API.
#
#   4. NODE.JS-ECOSYSTEM HISTORICAL DEFAULT — winston was the
#      default Node.js logger from 2011-2020 (the Express +
#      Node-services era).  Major historical adopters:
#         * Express middleware ecosystem (winston is the most
#           common Express logger in production deployments)
#         * NestJS (default logger before NestJS introduced its
#           own internal Logger)
#         * LoopBack (IBM's Node API framework)
#         * Sails.js, Hapi, Restify
#         * AWS Lambda Node runtime (recommended)
#         * Heroku Node.js examples (recommended)
#         * Many enterprise Node services from the 2014-2020
#           era that still run in production
#      Newer projects often choose pino for performance, but
#      winston's MASSIVE INSTALLED BASE means most Node
#      developers have used or maintained winston-using code.
#      Compare every other documented TS-Node logger — only
#      bunyan has comparable historical adoption, but winston
#      dominates by an order of magnitude.  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node logger with 2011-2020 default-status historical
#      provenance.
#
#   5. EXCEPTION + REJECTION HANDLER INTEGRATION — winston
#      provides built-in handlers for uncaught exceptions
#      AND unhandled promise rejections, automatically logging
#      them via the configured transports:
#
#          const logger = winston.createLogger({
#              transports: [new winston.transports.Console()],
#              exceptionHandlers: [
#                  new winston.transports.File({ filename: 'exceptions.log' }),
#              ],
#              rejectionHandlers: [
#                  new winston.transports.File({ filename: 'rejections.log' }),
#              ],
#          });
#
#      Compare:
#         * consola: panic handling via wrap helpers
#         * pino: requires separate pino.final() pattern
#         * bunyan: no built-in exception handling
#         * winston: BUILT-IN exceptionHandlers + rejectionHandlers
#                     as logger options
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with built-in uncaught-
#      exception + rejection-handler configuration.
#
# winston's relationship to other documented TS-Node libraries:
#
#   * Like consola (R576) — both are unified logging libraries
#                            with multiple output modes
#   * Unlike consola — winston has production-backend transport
#                       ecosystem (50+ community transports);
#                       consola has developer-console reporter
#                       abstraction (4 built-in reporters)
#   * Like @clack/prompts (R???) — both are general-purpose Node
#                                   libraries with rich features
#   * Unlike clack — winston is logging; clack is prompts
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: logrus (sirupsen/logrus) — similar transport
#                hook architecture (logrus.Hooks for multi-output)
#         * Rust: tracing-subscriber (with transports as Layers) +
#                  fern (with chainable dispatch)
#         * Python: stdlib logging (with multiple Handlers)
#     winston is the FIRST documented TS-Node logger with
#     production-grade multi-transport architecture for
#     backend-service deployment.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE peertube CLI — @commander-js/extra-typings + winston + prompts
#
# peertube's CLI is in apps/peertube-cli/src/peertube.ts (entry
# point) + apps/peertube-cli/src/peertube-*.ts (subcommands).
# Argv via @commander-js/extra-typings (typed Commander.js).
# Auth-required commands use winston for diagnostic logging:
#
#     import { Command } from '@commander-js/extra-typings';
#     import { createLogger, format, transports } from 'winston';
#     import { defineAuthProgram } from './peertube-auth.js';
#     import { defineUploadProgram } from './peertube-upload.js';
#     import { defineRedundancyProgram } from './peertube-redundancy.js';
#     import { definePluginsProgram } from './peertube-plugins.js';
#     import { defineGetAccessProgram } from './peertube-get-access-token.js';
#
#     const program = new Command()
#         .version(version, '-v, --version')
#         .usage('[command] [options]');
#
#     program.addCommand(defineAuthProgram());
#     program.addCommand(defineUploadProgram());
#     program.addCommand(defineRedundancyProgram());
#     program.addCommand(definePluginsProgram());
#     program.addCommand(defineGetAccessProgram());
#
# Top-level subcommands:
#   auth                 Register credentials for remote instances
#     add                Remember credentials for an instance
#     del <url>          Unregister a remote instance
#     list               List registered remote instances
#     set-default <url>  Set existing entry as default
#   upload               Upload a video to an instance
#   redundancy           Manage video redundancy
#     list-remote-redundancies  List remote redundancies on your videos
#     list-my-redundancies      List your redundancies of remote videos
#     add                       Duplicate a video into redundancy
#     remove                    Remove a video from redundancy
#   plugins              Manage plugins + themes
#     list               List installed plugins
#     install            Install a plugin or theme
#     update             Update a plugin or theme
#     uninstall          Uninstall a plugin or theme
#   get-access-token     Fetch an access token for direct API use
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented TS-Node logger:
#
#   1. TRANSPORT ECOSYSTEM (50+ COMMUNITY TRANSPORTS) — Every
#      other documented TS-Node logger has at most a handful of
#      built-in outputs.  winston has 50+ community transports
#      for production logging destinations.
#
#   2. FUNCTIONAL FORMAT COMPOSITION — Every other documented
#      TS-Node logger has fixed output formats.  winston uses
#      composable format transforms in pipelines.
#
#   3. PROFILE + QUERY INSTRUMENTATION — Every other documented
#      TS-Node logger lacks profile + query APIs.  winston has
#      both built-in.
#
#   4. EXCEPTION + REJECTION HANDLER OPTIONS — Every other
#      documented TS-Node logger requires manual setup for
#      uncaught-exception + rejection handling.  winston has
#      built-in exceptionHandlers + rejectionHandlers logger
#      options.
#
#   5. 2011-2020 NODE-ECOSYSTEM HISTORICAL DEFAULT — Every
#      other documented TS-Node logger emerged after 2018.
#      winston was the DEFAULT NODE LOGGER for nearly a decade
#      of Express + Node-services era development.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node logger with historical default-status
#      provenance.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/Chocobozzz/PeerTube/tree/develop/apps/peertube-cli/src/
# peertube-{auth,upload,redundancy,plugins,get-access-token}.ts files.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _pt_cmds
_pt_cmds=(
    'auth:register your accounts on remote PeerTube instances'
    'upload:upload a video to a PeerTube instance'
    'redundancy:manage video redundancy across instances'
    'plugins:manage PeerTube plugins and themes'
    'get-access-token:fetch an access token for direct API use'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[show version]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'peertube subcommand' _pt_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            auth)
                local -a _auth_sub
                _auth_sub=(
                    'add:remember your account on a remote instance'
                    'del:unregister a remote instance'
                    'list:list registered remote instances'
                    'set-default:set an existing entry as default'
                )
                if (( CURRENT == 2 )); then
                    _describe -t auth-cmd 'auth subcommand' _auth_sub
                else
                    case $words[2] in
                        add)
                            _arguments \
                                '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                                '(-u --url)'{-u+,--url=}'[server URL]:url:' \
                                '(-U --username)'{-U+,--username=}'[username]:user:' \
                                '(-p --password)'{-p+,--password=}'[password]:pass:' \
                                '--default[set as new default entry]' \
                                && ret=0
                            ;;
                        del|set-default)
                            _message 'instance URL'
                            ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                fi
                ;;
            upload)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '(-u --url)'{-u+,--url=}'[server URL]:url:' \
                    '(-U --username)'{-U+,--username=}'[username]:user:' \
                    '(-p --password)'{-p+,--password=}'[password]:pass:' \
                    '(-b --thumbnail)'{-b+,--thumbnail=}'[thumbnail path]:file:_files' \
                    '(-f --file)'{-f+,--file=}'[absolute video file path]:file:_files' \
                    '(-n --video-name)'{-n+,--video-name=}'[video name]:name:' \
                    '(-c --category)'{-c+,--category=}'[category number]:N:' \
                    '(-l --licence)'{-l+,--licence=}'[licence number]:N:' \
                    '(-L --language)'{-L+,--language=}'[language ISO 639 code]:lang:' \
                    '(-t --tags)'{-t+,--tags=}'[video tags (comma-separated)]:tags:' \
                    '(-N --nsfw)'{-N,--nsfw}'[video is Not Safe For Work]' \
                    '(-d --video-description)'{-d+,--video-description=}'[video description]:desc:' \
                    '(-P --privacy)'{-P+,--privacy=}'[privacy level (1=public,2=unlisted,3=private)]:N:' \
                    '(-C --channel-name)'{-C+,--channel-name=}'[channel name]:channel:' \
                    '--no-comments-enabled[disable video comments]' \
                    '(-s --support)'{-s+,--support=}'[video support text]:text:' \
                    '--no-wait-transcoding[do not wait transcoding before publishing]' \
                    '--no-download-enabled[disable video download]' \
                    '--verbose=[verbosity level (0..3)]:N:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            redundancy)
                local -a _red_sub
                _red_sub=(
                    'list-remote-redundancies:list remote redundancies on your videos'
                    'list-my-redundancies:list your redundancies of remote videos'
                    'add:duplicate a video into your redundancy system'
                    'remove:remove a video from your redundancies'
                )
                if (( CURRENT == 2 )); then
                    _describe -t redundancy-cmd 'redundancy subcommand' _red_sub
                fi
                ret=0
                ;;
            plugins)
                local -a _plug_sub
                _plug_sub=(
                    'list:list installed plugins'
                    'install:install a plugin or theme'
                    'update:update a plugin or theme'
                    'uninstall:uninstall a plugin or theme'
                )
                if (( CURRENT == 2 )); then
                    _describe -t plugins-cmd 'plugins subcommand' _plug_sub
                fi
                ret=0
                ;;
            get-access-token)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '(-u --url)'{-u+,--url=}'[server URL]:url:' \
                    '(-U --username)'{-U+,--username=}'[username]:user:' \
                    '(-p --password)'{-p+,--password=}'[password]:pass:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
